# 📚 Linux Theory

## Linux Users

A user is an account that can log in to a Linux system. Every user has a unique User ID (UID) and belongs to one or more groups.

### Types of Users

### 1. Root User

- Superuser of Linux
- Has unrestricted access to the entire system
- User ID (UID) = 0
- Can install software, create users, delete files, and modify system settings

---

### 2. Regular User

A standard user account used for daily work.

Example:

kp

Regular users have limited permissions and use `sudo` to perform administrative tasks.

---

### 3. System Users

These accounts are created automatically by Linux to run system services.

Examples:

- daemon
- www-data
- mysql
- nobody

These users usually cannot log in.

---

# Linux Groups

A group is a collection of users.

Groups simplify permission management by allowing multiple users to share access to files and directories.

Examples:

- sudo
- adm
- users

---

# Important Linux Files

## /etc/passwd

Stores basic information about all user accounts.

Information includes:

- Username
- UID
- GID
- Home Directory
- Default Shell

---

## /etc/group

Stores all groups available on the system.

Contains:

- Group Name
- Group ID
- Group Members

---

## /etc/shadow

Stores encrypted user passwords.

Only the root user can access this file.

---

# Commands Learned

| Command | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| whoami | Displays current user |
| who | Displays logged-in users |
| id | Displays UID, GID and groups |
| groups | Displays user groups |
| cat /etc/passwd | Lists user accounts |
| cat /etc/group | Lists system groups |
| echo $USER | Displays current username |
| echo $HOME | Displays home directory |
| echo $SHELL | Displays default shell |

